    l5p:currentCeiling "L5 on Generation-depth/Consumer-effort/Test-generation; L4 on Handler-gap/Regen-lifecycle/Target-API-fidelity; L3 on Ontology-expressiveness (see mat:tcps rows). cap06 CLOSED 2026-07-22 (wave3 tcps-cluster cell, worktree wf_8730e757-e2c-1): packs/tcps-core-pack/templates/pokayoke_sabotage_proof.rs.tmpl projects 12 new tcps:RangeGuardPassCase/FailCase + tcps:MatchGuardPassCase/FailCase individuals via a real sparql: frontmatter (no hardcoded EXPECTED array) into examples/tcps-generated/tests/tcps_core_pokayoke_sabotage_proof.rs, which calls the REAL 範囲防止/一致防止 guard structs' 検査する method (防止条件<入力> trait) directly -- not a subprocess ggen sync refusal, a runtime guard-logic proof. 5/5 tests passing (`cargo test --test tcps_core_pokayoke_sabotage_proof`): 3 range + 3 match positive controls, 3 range + 3 match adversarial-input fail cases, plus a SPARQL-row-count floor check. Non-vacuity independently verified: changed rgcFailBelowMinimum's tcps:rangeInput 99->150 (still declared a RangeGuardFailCase but now genuinely in-range), re-synced, re-ran -- got the predicted 4 passed/1 failed with a real assertion message ('guard fails OPEN, not closed'), then restored byte-for-byte (git diff shows pure insertion, no residual mutation) and re-synced to 5/5 green again. Idempotent: a second `ggen sync run` after restoration reports `tests/tcps_core_pokayoke_sabotage_proof.rs: skipped: unchanged: content identical` in the live receipt (not just claimed -- read directly from .ggen-v2/receipt.json's admission log), and the file's own sha256 was identical (f99e97e1...) across two independent full verify+sync cycles. Full `cargo test --workspace` green throughout (18+7+5+2+1 = 33 tests across the 4 tcps-* crates, 0 failures). `just verify-tcps` clean at the end (receipt valid:true, signed:true, signature_valid:true, 133 outputs)." ;
    l5p:missingCap l5p:cap08, l5p:cap10, l5p:cap11 ;
    l5p:nextPromotionObligation "cap06 closed 2026-07-22 (see currentCeiling). 3 capabilities remain open: cap08, cap10, cap11 -- investigated this pass (real findings, not yet closing any): cap08 (Generated provenance) -- confirmed still genuinely open: the live sync receipt (.ggen-v2/receipt.json) DOES carry a per-generated-file admission log (evidence_id + decision + reason, e.g. 'skipped: unchanged: content identical') and a pack-level content_hash table (ggen.lock), but neither traces a specific generated file to the SPECIFIC ontology individual(s) and template CONTENT VERSION that produced it -- only to the whole pack's aggregate hash. tcps-release-pack's own source_manifest_sha256.tmpl (packs/tcps-release-pack/templates/) looks like a candidate fix but is a hand-authored static blob (same literal-transcription pattern as its other templates), not a live-computed digest chain -- confirmed by reading it: it renders one hardcoded `tcps:artifactBody` literal verbatim, so it cannot be cap08's proof (this is also why tcps-release-pack's own missingCap still lists cap08). A real closure needs either an engine-level per-artifact provenance field (out of scope for pack-only work) or a new generated per-file header/manifest computed AT SYNC TIME from the actual consumed facts, plus a script that recomputes and checks it -- not attempted this pass, sizing it correctly matters more than a decorative stand-in (see coding-agent-mistakes.md's Decorative Completion class). cap10 (Generated release surface) -- tcps-release-pack (a sibling pack composed into the SAME examples/tcps-generated consumer) already generates the CI/packaging/release surface for the TCPS family as a whole, so tcps-core-pack's own missingCap here may be double-counting rather than a real independent gap; not adjudicated this pass -- needs a decision on whether cap10 is scored per-pack or per-ecosystem-composition before further work, not a fabricated closure either way. cap11 (Generated evolution path)